### Henry Lee III (January 29, 1756 – March 25, 1818)

Henry Lee III, a man whose life was a tapestry woven with threads of [Patriotism](/Patriot_(American_Revolution)) and political maneuvering, served as the ninth [Governor of Virginia](/Governor_of_Virginia) and represented his state in the United States Congress. His exploits during the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution), particularly his audacious maneuvers as a [cavalry](/Cavalry) officer in the [Continental Army](/Continental_Army), earned him the indelible moniker "Light-Horse Harry." It’s worth noting, for those who might have missed the memo, that he was also the father of [Robert E. Lee](/Robert_E._Lee), a figure whose subsequent military leadership during the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War) would cast a long, complex shadow.

#### Early Life and Education

Lee emerged from the privileged soil of [Leesylvania Plantation](/Leesylvania_(plantation)) in [Prince William County](/Prince_William_County), within the then-Colony of Virginia. His lineage was not insignificant; he was the son of [Col. Henry Lee II](/Henry_Lee_II) and Lucy Grymes. His father held the distinction of being a first cousin to [Richard Henry Lee](/Richard_Henry_Lee), a man who would eventually preside over the [Continental Congress](/President_of_the_Continental_Congress). His mother, furthermore, was an aunt to the wife of [Virginia Governor](/Virginia_Governor) [Thomas Nelson Jr.](/Thomas_Nelson_Jr.). The family tree, as is often the case with such prominent lineages, extended further back, connecting him to figures like President [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson) through his great-grandmother Mary Bland. He could also trace his ancestry to [Henry Lee I](/Henry_Lee_I), [Richard Bland](/Richard_Bland_(burgess)), [William Randolph](/William_Randolph), [Theodorick Bland of Westover](/Theodorick_Bland_of_Westover), and Governor [Richard Bennett](/Richard_Bennett_(Governor)). A veritable who's who of colonial Virginia, really.

His formal education concluded at the College of New Jersey, now known as [Princeton University](/Princeton_University), in 1773. Following this, he embarked on the predictable path of pursuing a legal career, a pursuit he likely abandoned with little regret when the drums of war began to beat.

#### Career

##### American Revolutionary War

The moment the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) erupted at the [Battles of Lexington and Concord](/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord) in 1775, Lee was ready. He swiftly assumed the role of [captain](/Captain_(land)) in a [dragoon](/Dragoon) detachment from the [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia), a unit that was subsequently integrated into the [1st Continental Light Dragoons](/1st_Continental_Light_Dragoons).

By 1778, Lee had ascended to the rank of [major](/Major_(United_States)). He was then entrusted with the command of a composite unit, a blend of cavalry and infantry, which he christened [Lee's Legion](/Lee%27s_Legion). It was with this command that he began to forge the reputation that would define him. Highly mobile units, such as light cavalry, were indispensable during this period. They executed critical reconnaissance missions, engaged enemy forces during troop movements, disrupted supply lines, conducted daring raids, and penetrated enemy territory for strategic expeditions. These tactics, in essence, laid the groundwork for what we now recognize as [guerrilla warfare](/Guerrilla_warfare) and [maneuver warfare](/Maneuver_warfare).

In August of that year, Lee led a detachment in a daring raid on a British fort, culminating in the [Battle of Paulus Hook](/Battle_of_Paulus_Hook) in New Jersey. The engagement resulted in the neutralization of 50 enemy soldiers and the capture of 158, while the American forces sustained minimal losses. Despite this clear success, a faction of his fellow officers, perhaps driven by envy or a desire to assert authority, initiated court-martial proceedings against him on eight charges. Fortunately, [George Washington](/George_Washington), then Commander-in-Chief, saw through the machility, and Lee was acquitted on all counts. [4] In September, Lee's dragoons distinguished themselves again by defeating a Hessian regiment at the [Battle of Edgar's Lane](/Battle_of_Edgar%27s_Lane).

It was during his tenure commanding the Legion that Lee acquired the nickname "Light-Horse Harry," a testament to his prowess in the saddle. The Continental Congress, recognizing his exceptional service, voted on September 22, 1779, to present Lee with a gold medal – an honor typically reserved for officers of general rank. [5][6]

Lee was subsequently promoted to [lieutenant colonel](/Lieutenant_colonel) and assigned with his Legion to the less predictable southern theater. In January 1781, Lee's Legion, in conjunction with General [Francis Marion](/Francis_Marion), launched an assault on a British outpost at [Georgetown, South Carolina](/Georgetown,_South_Carolina). The following month, he played a role in screening the British Army during their strategic movement toward the Dan River. Throughout the spring of 1781, Lee, alongside Generals Francis Marion and [Andrew Pickens](/Andrew_Pickens_(congressman)), achieved the capture of several key British outposts scattered across South Carolina and Georgia. These included [Fort Watson](/Siege_of_Fort_Watson), [Fort Motte](/Fort_Motte), [Fort Granby](/Granby,_South_Carolina), Fort Galphin, Fort Grierson, and [Fort Cornwallis](/Augusta,_Georgia). [7] Lee and his legion also participated in the pivotal [Battle of Guilford Court House](/Battle_of_Guilford_Court_House), the arduous [Siege of Ninety-Six](/Siege_of_Ninety-Six), and the fiercely contested [Battle of Eutaw Springs](/Battle_of_Eutaw_Springs). He was present at the surrender of [Charles Cornwallis](/Charles_Cornwallis,_1st_Marquess_Cornwallis) at [Yorktown](/Battle_of_Yorktown_(1781)), but he soon departed the Army, citing exhaustion and what he perceived as inadequate recognition from his peers.

Colonel Lee was also a founding member of the Virginia [Society of the Cincinnati](/Society_of_the_Cincinnati), a fraternal organization for officers of the Continental Army.

##### Post-War Career

Following the war, Lee transitioned into the political arena. From 1786 to 1788, he served as a delegate to the [Congress of the Confederation](/Congress_of_the_Confederation). In 1788, he lent his voice and influence to the Virginia convention, advocating for the ratification of the [United States Constitution](/United_States_Constitution). His political career continued in the [Virginia General Assembly](/Virginia_General_Assembly) from 1789 to 1791, after which he ascended to the position of [Governor of Virginia](/List_of_Governors_of_Virginia), serving from 1791 to 1794. During his governorship, the Commonwealth saw fit to name a new county, [Lee County, Virginia](/Lee_County,_Virginia), in his honor. [8]

In 1794, President [George Washington](/George_Washington) called upon Lee to quell the [Whiskey Rebellion](/Whiskey_Rebellion) in western Pennsylvania. Lee led a substantial force of 12,950 militiamen, but the insurrection dissolved without bloodshed due to a swift and peaceful surrender. In 1798, with tensions escalating towards a potential conflict with France, Henry Lee was appointed a [major general](/Major_General) in the [U.S. Army](/United_States_Army).

It was at the funeral of George Washington on December 26, 1799, that Lee delivered his most enduring words, famously eulogizing the former president as "first in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen." [9]

From 1799 to 1801, he represented Virginia in the [United States House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) as a member of the [Federalist Party](/Federalist_Party). After concluding his public service in 1801, he returned to [Stratford Hall](/Stratford_Hall_(plantation)) to manage his family and plantation, a venture that proved less successful than his military campaigns. The economic downturn of the [Panic of 1796–1797](/Panic_of_1796%E2%80%931797) and the financial ruin of [Robert Morris](/Robert_Morris_(financier)) significantly depleted Lee's fortune.

In 1808, President [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson) reappointed him as major-general in anticipation of a possible war with Great Britain, and Lee subsequently organized the Virginia militia. This period, however, was marked by personal hardship. In 1809, he declared bankruptcy and was incarcerated in [debtors' prison](/Debtors%27_prison) in [Montross, Virginia](/Montross,_Virginia) for a year. His son, Robert, was merely two years old at the time. Upon his release, Lee relocated his family to [Alexandria, Virginia](/Alexandria,_Virginia).

#### Later Life and Death

Lee's hopes for a military commission at the outset of the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812) were dashed, despite his appeal to President [James Madison](/James_Madison). In 1812, he published his *Memoirs of the War in the Southern Department of the United States*, a narrative account of his military experiences during the [Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War).

The year 1812 also brought a brutal episode in Baltimore, Maryland. During a period of civil unrest, Lee sustained severe injuries while attempting to defend his friend, [Alexander Contee Hanson](/Alexander_Contee_Hanson), the editor of the Baltimore newspaper, *The Federal Republican*. The mob, fueled by [Democratic-Republican](/Democratic-Republican_Party) opposition to the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), targeted Hanson's paper. Lee, Hanson, and approximately two dozen other Federalists sought refuge within the newspaper offices. The following day, they surrendered to city officials and were subsequently jailed. [Needs clarification] However, a mob, incited by a laborer named George Woolslager, breached the jail. The Federalists were subjected to a horrific three-hour ordeal of beating and torture. Many were gravely injured, and one Federalist, [James Lingan](/James_Lingan), died as a result. [11][12]

Lee's injuries were extensive, including severe internal damage and wounds to his head and face, which even affected his speech. The symptoms he exhibited are now understood to be consistent with [post-traumatic stress disorder](/Post-traumatic_stress_disorder). His recovery at home proved unsuccessful, prompting him to sail to the [West Indies](/Caribbean) in search of healing. En route back to Virginia, he succumbed to his injuries on March 25, 1818, at [Dungeness](/Dungeness_(Cumberland_Island,_Georgia)), located on [Cumberland Island](/Cumberland_Island), Georgia. He was attended in his final days by Louisa, the daughter of [Nathanael Greene](/Nathanael_Greene). "Light-Horse Harry" was interred with full military honors, rendered by an American fleet stationed near [St. Marys, Georgia](/St._Marys,_Georgia), in a modest cemetery at Dungeness. In 1913, his remains were relocated to the Lee family crypt within the [University Chapel](/University_Chapel), situated on the grounds of [Washington & Lee University](/Washington_%26_Lee_University) in [Lexington, Virginia](/Lexington,_Virginia).

#### Personal Life and Family

Between April 8 and 13, 1782, at [Stratford Hall](/Stratford_Hall_(plantation)), Lee married his second cousin, Matilda Ludwell Lee, often referred to as "the Divine Matilda." She was the daughter of Philip Ludwell Lee Sr. and Elizabeth Steptoe. Matilda bore him three children before her untimely death in 1790:

*   Philip Ludwell Lee (1784–1794)
*   Lucy Grymes Lee (1786–1860)
*   [Henry Lee IV](/Henry_Lee_IV) (May 28, 1787 – January 30, 1837), who would later distinguish himself as a historian and author, and even served as a speechwriter for figures like [John C. Calhoun](/John_C._Calhoun) and presidential candidate [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson), assisting the latter with his inaugural address.

On June 18, 1793, Lee took as his second wife the affluent [Anne Hill Carter](/Anne_Hill_Carter_Lee) at [Shirley Plantation](/Shirley_Plantation). Anne was the daughter of Charles Carter, Esq., of Shirley, and his second wife, Ann Butler Moore. Ann Butler Moore's lineage could be traced back to Sir [Thomas More](/Thomas_More), and her mother, Ann Catherine Spotswood, was the daughter of Virginia Governor [Alexander Spotswood](/Alexander_Spotswood). This maternal connection extended further, linking Anne to figures such as [John Spotswood](/John_Spotswood) and, astonishingly, King [Robert II of Scotland](/Robert_II_of_Scotland) through his daughter Elizabeth Stewart. [15][16] Together, Henry and Anne had six children:

*   Algernon Sidney Lee (April 2, 1795 – August 9, 1796), who died at [Sully](/Sully_(Fairfax_County,_Virginia)) Plantation and was buried there without a marker. [17]
*   Charles Carter Lee (1798–1871)
*   Anne Kinloch Lee (1800–1864)
*   [Sydney Smith Lee](/Sydney_Smith_Lee) (1802–1869)
*   [Robert Edward Lee](/Robert_E._Lee) (January 19, 1807 – October 12, 1870). The fifth child of Henry and Anne, he would rise to become the general-in-chief of the [Confederate](/Confederate_States_Army) forces during the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War).
*   Mildred Lee (1811–1856)

It is through Anne Hill Carter that Lee is an ancestor of [Helen Keller](/Helen_Keller).

#### In Popular Culture

Screenwriter [Robert Rodat](/Robert_Rodat) has stated that the fictional Colonel Harry Burwell, a character in the 2000 film [The Patriot](/The_Patriot_(2000_film)), was inspired by the actual exploits of Henry Lee. [18]

In the 1969 musical [1776](/1776_(musical)), Lee's nickname is mentioned, albeit anachronistically, within the song "The Lees of Old Virginia," performed by his elder cousin, [Richard Henry Lee](/Richard_Henry_Lee).

Henry Lee III was a member of the [Society of the Cincinnati](/Society_of_the_Cincinnati) in the State of Virginia. [19]

